{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567258","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567258"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:58:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:58:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18954"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18954","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18954"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.02,0.03,0.02,0.92]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11688"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110294"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11688"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18954"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92565"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"18"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4986"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4989"},{"type":"tags","id":"4990"},{"type":"tags","id":"5759"},{"type":"tags","id":"11260"},{"type":"tags","id":"11304"},{"type":"tags","id":"11336"},{"type":"tags","id":"11645"},{"type":"tags","id":"11648"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12867"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27500"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27501"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44854"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110294","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110294"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA newly qualified doctor is discussing professional obligations and conscientious objection with their supervisor. They want to understand which healthcare services they can decline to provide based on personal moral or religious beliefs, while still maintaining their professional obligations.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following services can a doctor decline to provide under conscientious objection, provided appropriate referral is made?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Emergency caesarean section for foetal distress","Pain relief for a terminally ill patient","Treatment for a sexually transmitted infection","Basic life support for a cardiac arrest","Elective termination of pregnancy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Eelective termination of pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E. Healthcare providers can conscientiously object to providing non-emergency procedures like elective terminations, provided they refer the patient to another qualified provider who can deliver the service.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmergency caesarean section for foetal distress\u003C/strong\u003E - Emergency care cannot be refused as it would breach the duty of care and potentially harm both mother and baby.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBasic life support for a cardiac arrest\u003C/strong\u003E - Emergency resuscitation is a fundamental duty that cannot be declined.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETreatment for a sexually transmitted infection\u003C/strong\u003E - Refusing treatment for medical conditions based on how they were acquired would constitute discrimination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPain relief for a terminally ill patient\u003C/strong\u003E - Withholding pain relief would violate the principle of beneficence and constitute patient abandonment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile healthcare providers have the right to conscientiously object to certain non-emergency procedures, they must:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInform their employer/colleagues of their position\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERefer patients to alternative providers\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENot abandon or discriminate against patients\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProvide emergency care regardless of personal beliefs\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Healthcare providers have a right to conscientious objection for procedures that conflict with their personal beliefs, but must refer patients appropriately.","Emergency care cannot be refused under conscientious objection as it would violate the duty of care.","Conscientious objection must not result in discrimination based on protected characteristics like gender, race, or sexuality."],"references":["Van Norman GA. Conscientious Objection. Anesthesiol Clin. 2024 Sep;42(3):539-554. doi: 10.1016/j.anclin.2023.11.004. Epub 2024 Feb 29. PMID: 39054026. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/39054026/","Shanawani H. The Challenges of Conscientious Objection in Health care. J Relig Health. 2016 Apr;55(2):384-93. doi: 10.1007/s10943-016-0200-4. PMID: 26923838. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26923838/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92565"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18954"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92565","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92565"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-29T15:11:53+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-29T15:11:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11688"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110294"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"18","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/18"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddd1\u200d\u2696\ufe0f","name":"M